column1: Between 29 October 2021 and 30 June 2022, how many members will announce their withdrawal from the Cooperation between China and Central and Eastern European Countries (China-CEEC) initiative?

column6: it seems even though China continue to support Russia, CEE countries are unwilling to break from the 16+1 initiative. One possible reason is that the initiative has become less relevant today.
The Czech Republic is considering an exit from China’s 16+1 investment platform for Central and Eastern Europe.

On the one hand, if by now (May 9, 2022) the states in question have not left, unless strengthening political ties to Taiwan makes an overwhelmingly compelling business and political case, CEEC states continue to hope to benefit from BRI mega project funding.

Only about 3.5 countries[1] withdraw from international organizations every year.
